		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2017"></a><br><code>sle2017/paper20</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Robust projectional editing</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/FriedrichSteimann.html">Friedrich Steimann</a>, <a href="../profile/MarcusFrenkel.html">Marcus Frenkel</a>, <a href="../profile/MarkusVölter.html">Markus Völter</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136034">10.1145/3136014.3136034</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The paper addresses projectional editor technology and how to make projectional editing more robust.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> It emphasizes enforcing well-formedness rules (static constraints) in addition to metamodel conformance.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> A key goal is improving user experience by preventing/handling ill-formed intermediate states during editing.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It discusses how editing constraints interact with composed language fragments and their well-formedness rules.
</li></ul></li></ul>
